While `G_MUTEX_AUTO_LOCK` calls the `g_mutex_lock()` and `g_mutex_unlock()` methods, `GS_MUTEX_AUTO_GUARD` calls the `g_mutex_init()` and `g_mutex_clear()` methods, so they don't guard the same invariants.

What I tried to explain in this comment is that `GS_MUTEX_AUTO_GUARD` is similar but not equivalent to the following:
```c
{
    g_auto(GMutex) lock;

    g_mutex_init (&lock);
    /* 'lock' will automatically be cleared here as we leave the scope. */
}
```

The first and main difference is we can only use `g_auto()` when declaring an individual variable on the stack, so we can't use autocleanup on existing locks, e.g. in structs on on the heap. `GS_MUTEX_AUTO_GUARD` allows us to use autocleanup on any already existing lock. So we can't use it.

We can only file variables for autocleanup when declaring them, and we can't declare a mutex and initialize it in a single expression, meaning with `g_auto(GMutex)` we can only file a mutex for autocleanup while leaving it in an undefined state, yikes. The second difference is `GS_MUTEX_AUTO_GUARD` decorrelates the declaration from the other steps, which allows it to both initializ an existing mutex and to file it for autocleanup in a single expression.

I actually use both `G_MUTEX_AUTO_LOCK` and `GS_MUTEX_AUTO_GUARD` side by side in this file, as they are complementary, e.g.:
```c
GS_MUTEX_AUTO_GUARD (&monitor.lock, lock); /* inits monitor.lock */
GS_COND_AUTO_GUARD (&monitor.cond, cond); /* inits monitor.cond */
G_MUTEX_AUTO_LOCK (&monitor.lock, locker); /* locks monitor.lock */
/* unlocks monitor.lock */
/* clears monitor.cond */
/* clears monitor.lock */
```

`G_MUTEX_AUTO_LOCK` was a source of inspiration, I tried to create something that would mix well with the existing tooling.

