This won’t return the correct value if `error == NULL`. In that case, an error might have happened, but the caller didn’t provide a way for it to be reported. It would be correct to return `FALSE` in that situation (because an error did happen), rather than `TRUE`.

The normal pattern for this is to use a local error variable:
```c
GError *local_error = NULL;

appinfo = g_task_propagate_pointer (G_TASK (result), &local_error);
if (local_error != NULL) {
	g_propagate_error (error, g_steal_pointer (&local_error));
	return FALSE;
} else if (appinfo == NULL) {
	/* App is not supported by this plugin */
	return TRUE;
}
```
